{
  "texts": [
    "Research gapDespite the significant advancements in LLMs, their integration into educational systems remains fragmented, with several critical gaps in the current literature:• Lack of Structured Frameworks for Integration: Existing studies primarily focus on isolated applications of LLMs, such as automated content creation, language tutoring, and intelligent tutoring systems [25,34,35].",
    "However, these studies fail to provide a structured, theoretical framework to guide the integration of LLMs into education while addressing scalability, adaptability, and ethical challenges.",
    "• Limited Research on Ethical and Pedagogical Challenges: While LLMs offer opportunities for personalized learning, significant concerns remain about data privacy, algorithmic bias, and ethical deployment [9,22,37].",
    "Current literature lacks a comprehensive approach to balancing the pedagogical benefits of LLMs with the need to ensure ethical AI usage in education.• Insufficient Exploration of Multi-Contextual Adaptability: Most existing studies focus on specific educational settings (e.g., higher education) or particular tasks (e.g., grading automation or question answering) [7,10,12].There is limited exploration of how LLMs can adapt to diverse learning environments, including K-12 education, distance learning, and blended classrooms.",
    "• Absence of Comparative Analysis and Real-World Applications: Few studies offer real-world case studies or comparative analyses of LLM implementations across educational contexts."
  ]
}